# Tables and figures

This chapter shows a few simple examples of including tables and figures.

## `knitr` table

This is an example knitr table. We can reference @tbl-tbl1 easily and it is auto-numbered. See the `Table1.Rmd` for how to get auto-numbering to work in Quarto.










::: {.cell}

:::

<!-- Use format="pandoc" if you are going to Word. knitr often gets confused if you don't and you'll drive yourself crazy wondering why the same kable() command doesn't show the same table in Word (hint, its because unbeknownst to you, the format argument value on you). -->

::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
Table: This is a basic table with an unnumbered caption.

                    mpg    cyl    disp 
------------------  ----  -----  ------
Mazda RX4           21      6     160  
Mazda RX4 Wag       21      6     160  
Datsun 710          23      4     108  
Hornet 4 Drive      21      6     258  
Hornet Sportabout   19      8     360
:::
:::

::: {#tbl-tbl1 .cell tbl-cap='This is a table with a number. Getting the auto-numbering to work is different with Quarto. See the code.'}
::: {.cell-output-display}

## flextable

This is an example from the flextable help doc. We can reference @tbl-flex easily and it is auto-numbered. Donec bibendum pharetra arcu vitae porttitor. Morbi ac quam nunc. Ut cursus dolor a mauris aliquet vulputate. Morbi elementum ullamcorper augue, et tincidunt libero facilisis posuere. Nam congue velit non elit sollicitudin aliquet. Donec lobortis nunc ligula, id sollicitudin erat rhoncus cursus. Ut egestas orci libero, eu malesuada ex sollicitudin sed. Sed ornare nunc eget massa scelerisque, nec egestas nulla commodo. Pellentesque efficitur accumsan ullamcorper. Nulla facilisi. Maecenas tristique luctus malesuada. Phasellus id enim maximus, tempus tellus eu, dignissim sapien. Integer et mauris in lectus condimentum pellentesque non a felis.

## Cross-references

In Quarto, [table links](https://quarto.org/docs/authoring/cross-references.html#tables) use the table label `@tbl-tablabel` where `tablabel` is the label you put on the table chunk. In the text it looks like this @tbl-tablabel. The chunk yaml looks like this

```
#| label: tbl-tablabel
#| tbl-cap: "my caption"
```


::: {#tbl-tablabel .cell tbl-cap='This is a table with a number.'}
::: {.cell-output-display}
mpg    cyl    disp 
---------------  ----  -----  ------
Mazda RX4        21      6     160  
Mazda RX4 Wag    21      6     160  
Datsun 710       23      4     108  
Hornet 4 Drive   21      6     258
:::
:::


## Dynamic table captions

You can create captions dynamically.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
tbl_cap <- paste("This is a dynamically created caption. The length of mtcars is", nrow(mtcars), "rows")
```
:::


Unfortunately you cannot dynamically create your chunk labels too.
